			<h4><a id="comment_link_64210996" name="comment_link_64210996" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23214298&amp;cid=64210996" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64210996)" >Internal pressure/flow</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64210996" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64210996); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~PPH">PPH</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~PPH">( 736903 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64210996"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64210996"><p>This is not really surprising. While the forward sprinkler operates on conservation of momentum (mass of water traveling along a velocity vector), the reverse system inflow suction draws water from all directions, canceling out most of that momentum effect.
</p><p>However, flow inside the nozzles is (more or less) laminar. Giving it a defined velocity vector and momentum. Also, any change in direction creates additional velocity vectors which need to be resolved.
</p><p>I would think that actual pressure distribution ins<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

